            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sofia Reyes-Jones is a product of San Francisco\u2019s rich, overlapping cultures. Born in the late 70s, she was raised in a vibrant, cacophonous Mission District apartment, the daughter of a pragmatic Mexican-American muralist mother and an idealistic Anglo-American jazz musician father. Her childhood was a collage of wet paint, the scent of *carnitas* from the corner taqueria, and the soulful wail of a saxophone. This fusion of visual art and raw, improvisational sound became the bedrock of her identity.\n\nHer educational path was a direct line from this upbringing. After an undergraduate degree in Art History at UC Berkeley, she pursued a specialized MFA in Curatorial Practice in New York, hungry to understand the architecture behind art's impact. She returned to San Francisco armed with a sharp eye and a desire to create exhibitions that felt alive. She started as an assistant curator, meticulously climbing the ladder over two decades. Her current role as Director of Exhibitions at a multidisciplinary arts center in SoMa is the culmination of that climb.\n\nA key turning point was the end of her seven-year relationship with a tech executive five years ago. The breakup, a quiet clash of his world of scalable metrics versus her world of intangible cultural value, was painful but clarifying. It solidified her commitment to the arts and her own identity, independent of the city\u2019s dominant industry.\n\nNow 46, Sofia\u2019s life is a study in deliberate routine. Her mornings begin with a MUNI bus ride from her rent-controlled apartment, just blocks from where she grew up. Her days are a whirlwind of managing artists, budgets, and installations. Evenings are for gallery openings, intimate dinners with a tight circle of fellow artists and academics, or quiet nights sketching. She is deeply connected to her neighborhood, lamenting its gentrification while fiercely supporting its legacy businesses. Sofia\u2019s deepest aspiration is to curate a landmark retrospective of Bay Area art that bridges the pre-tech bohemians with today\u2019s digital creators. Personally, she hopes to find a partnership built on shared passions rather than proximity, proving that in a city obsessed with the new, things of lasting substance can still thrive."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe is seven years old, curled on the living room floor while her father coaxes a mournful melody from his saxophone. The sharp scent of turpentine hangs in the air from her mother\u2019s canvases. On the floor, her mother has sketched the outline for a new community mural on butcher paper. Sofia traces the powerful figures with her small finger, the music and the art merging into one inseparable feeling. It was not just a home; it was a perfect synthesis\u2014the moment she understood that all creative expression came from the same soulful place.\n\n2.\nAt twenty-eight, as a new assistant curator, she faced a notoriously difficult installation artist. He felt his work was being mishandled. Instead of arguing logistics, Sofia quietly spoke of how his piece's frenetic energy reminded her of a Pharoah Sanders solo her father used to play. The artist stopped, looked at her, and truly saw her for the first time. In that moment of shared understanding, she realized her bicultural, art-and-music-filled childhood wasn't just her history; it was her unique curatorial language, the key to bridging worlds.\n\n3.\nThe end came not with a fight, but over dinner. Her partner, glowing with excitement, showed her a graph on his phone. \u201cLook at that user retention curve,\u201d he\u2019d said, \u201cIsn\u2019t it beautiful?\u201d Sofia looked from the cold, glowing chart to his face and felt a profound, silent chasm open between them. His world was scalable data; hers was a singular, priceless brushstroke. The heartbreak was immense, but the clarity was a gift. She knew, with absolute certainty, she could never again try to translate her soul into a metric.\n\n4.\nJust last year, walking down 24th Street, she stopped cold. The old panaderia, with its phantom smell of warm *conchas* that defined her childhood Sunday mornings, was gone. In its place was a sterile, white-walled juice bar. A wave of unexpected, hollow grief hit her. It was more than just a shop; it was an erasure of memory. That moment hardened her resolve, turning passive nostalgia into a fierce, active mission to protect and champion the city\u2019s surviving cultural anchors before they, too, vanished.\n\n5.\nDuring a recent late-night installation, a young digital artist mentioned his inspiration: a faded Mission mural from the 80s. Sofia\u2019s heart leaped\u2014it was one of her mother\u2019s early collaborations. She pulled up a grainy photo of it on her phone. Seeing the young artist\u2019s eyes light up, recognizing the direct, unbroken line from her mother\u2019s hand to his code, was electrifying. The retrospective she dreamed of ceased to be an abstract ambition. It became a tangible, urgent story she was uniquely born to tell."
